y consumption\n- node disk read I/O consumption \n- node disk write I/O consumption \n- node disk space consumption\n\nAnomaly Cluster Description:\nBetween 09:25 and 09:29, a concentrated set of 17 anomalies included consistent garbage collector memory usage issues in adservice, container memory cache anomalies on node-6.cartservice2-0, repeated mesh HTTP request anomalies in frontend2-0, and increased UDP input errors on node-5. The emailservice also logged DNS resolution errors for jaeger-collector. This cluster reflects widespread performance degradation and networking errors spanning runtime, container, mesh, and node-level metrics, indicating a multi-layered failure likely initiated by resource contention or network instability impacting multiple services.\n\nRelevant Historical Incidents (if any):\n[Past Incident 1] (Score: 0.502)\nComponent: SDN controller | Metrics: N/A\nSummary: Component: SDN controller\nEvent: Some customers may experience API performance issues using the service. Errors are occurring when customers are attempting to create or modify Container Clusters. Some users may also experience API performance issues using Managed DNS console.  Engineers are actively investigating the issue. SERVICES(S): Container Clusters REGION(S): all regions EVENT START TIME: Sept 10, 2018 13:46 UTC NEXT UPDATE:  15:45 UTC\nSystem Type: cloud networking\nSymptoms: API performance issues; errors when creating or modifying Container Clusters; API performance issues using Managed DNS console\nAffected Metrics: None\nRoot Cause Category: maintenance-triggered cascading failure\nFailure Pattern: During a scheduled maintenance window, the SDN controller was updated without proper rollback safeguards, causing a temporary loss of network state consistency. This inconsistency led to API calls for Container Cluster creation and DNS management to time out or fail, resulting in degraded performance for users interacting with these services.\nMitigation Principles: Implement automated rollback procedures; enforce health checks before and after updates; use canary deployments; maintain redundant SDN controllers; isolate maintenance windows; validate configuration changes; monitor API latency and error rates\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased on this information, identify the MOST LIKELY root cause component and reason from the candidate list.\nFollow these rules:\n- The root cause must be a single component from the candidate list.\n- The reason must be directly supported by the anomaly description.\n- Assign a suspicious score between 0.0 and 1.0 (higher = more confident).\n\nRespond ONLY with a JSON object in this exact format:\n{\n    "component": "service-name",\n    "reason": "brief reason",\n    "score": 0.92\n}'}]
