disk write I/O consumption \n- node disk space consumption\n\nAnomaly Cluster Description:\nDuring 08:49 to 08:56 CST, sustained anomalies appeared involving repeated high garbage collection memory usage in adservice, ongoing CPU throttling in emailservice on node-5, persistent elevated latency in the istio-egressgateway, and increased duration in checkoutservice to currencyservice interactions. Log anomalies reappeared on checkoutservice-2. This cluster reflects a recurring or amplified resource contention issue impacting multiple layers: runtime memory pressure on adservice, CPU throttling limiting emailservice performance, and mesh-level latency spikes, collectively contributing to service latency increases downstream.\n\nRelevant Historical Incidents (if any):\n[Past Incident 1] (Score: 0.409)\nComponent: node-4 | Metrics: CPU, GC, HTTP, load, memory, rr, rt, utilization\nSummary: Component: node-4\nEvent: node-4 failure at 2022-03-20 17:12:41\nSystem Type: Banking Microservice (node)\nSymptoms: node CPU spike; The `Metric Node Anomaly Report` shows multiple anomalies for `node-5` starting around 17:12, including `system.cpu.pct_usage`, `system.load.15`, and `system.mem.used`, confirming host-level stress. N; The `Metric Container Anomaly Report` shows numerous, persistent anomalies for `adservice` pods on `node-5` (e.g., `node-5.adservice-0`, `node-5.adservice-1`) beginning at 17:12. Key metrics include `; The `Metric Runtime Anomaly Report` for `adservice.ts:8088` and `adservice2.ts:8088` indicates severe application-level problems starting at 17:12, with anomalies in `java_lang_OperatingSystem_SystemC\nAffected Metrics: CPU, GC, HTTP, load, memory, rr, rt, utilization\nRoot Cause Category: The incident, described as a CPU spike on `node-4`, is not supported by the provided anomaly data. Instead, the evidence overwhelmingly points to a re\nFailure Pattern: The incident, described as a CPU spike on `node-4`, is not supported by the provided anomaly data. Instead, the evidence overwhelmingly points to a resource exhaustion issue on `node-5` starting at 2022-03-20 17:12:00 UTC+8. The root cause was the `adservice` application, with multiple pods running on `node-5`, experiencing high CPU utilization, excessive Garbage Collection (GC), and memory pressure. This application-level stress led to container CPU throttling and a subsequent CPU and memory spike on the host `node-5`.\nMitigation Principles: 1. Investigate the `adservice` application for performance bottlenecks, such as memory leaks or inefficient code causing excessive GC, which are exacerbated by traffic spikes. 2. Review and adjust the CPU and memory limits for the `adservice` containers to either provide more resources or prevent a single service from overwhelming a node. 3. Verify the accuracy of the monitoring system\'s ground truth labeling, as the provided evidence contradicts the reported failure location (`node-4` vs. `node-5`).\n\nBackgroud:\n"\n\n\nBased on this information, identify the MOST LIKELY root cause component and reason from the candidate list.\nFollow these rules:\n- The root cause must be a single component from the candidate list.\n- The reason must be directly supported by the anomaly description.\n- Assign a suspicious score between 0.0 and 1.0 (higher = more confident).\n\nRespond ONLY with a JSON object in this exact format:\n{\n    "component": "service-name",\n    "reason": "brief reason",\n    "score": 0.92\n}'}]
